174–Afdød","1170–1252":"1170–1252","1193–Male":"1193–Afdød","1204–1258":"1204–1258","1148–Male":"1148–Afdød","1150–Female":"1150–Afdød","about 1193":"omkring 1193","Abt 1204":"omkring 1204","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","Abt 1174":"omkring 1174","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","Abt 1193":"omkring 1193","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Skipwith, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Jórvík, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1174–":"circa 1174–Overleden","1174–Female":"1174–Overleden","1170–1252":"1170–1252","1193–Male":"1193–Overleden","1204–1258":"1204–1258","1148–Male":"1148–Overleden","1150–Female":"1150–Overleden","about 1193":"circa 1193","Abt 1204":"circa 1204","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","Abt 1174":"circa 1174","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","Abt 1193":"circa 1193","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Skipwith, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1174–":"about 1174–Deceased","1174–Female":"1174–Deceased","1170–1252":"1170–1252","1193–Male":"1193–Deceased","1204–1258":"1204–1258","1148–Male":"1148–Deceased","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","about 1193":"about 1193","Abt 1204":"about 1204","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","Abt 1174":"about 1174","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","Abt 1193":"about 1193","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Skipwith, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish (Lowlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bell</i>. As a man's name this is from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘handsome’, which was also used as a nickname. As a female name it represents a short form of   Isabel  .","English (northern) and Scottish (Lowlands): from Middle English <i>belle</i> ‘bell’ (Old English <i>belle</i>), in various applications; most probably a metonymic occupational name for a bell ringer or bell maker, or a topographic name for someone living ‘at the bell’ (as attested by 14th-century forms such as <i>John atte Belle</i>). This indicates either residence by an actual bell (e.g. a town's bell in a bell tower, centrally placed to summon meetings, sound the alarm, etc.) or ‘at the sign of the bell’, i.e. a house or inn sign (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in Scots and English).","English: from Middle English <i>bel</i> ‘fair, fine, good’ (Old French <i>bel</i> ‘beautiful, fair’). See also   Beal   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alfonso, Alvarado, Augusto, Belia, Josefina, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Romero, Santa.","French, Spanish, Portuguese, and English (of French origin): from the Old French female personal name <i>Isabel</i>, which is first recorded in late 11th-century Paris and Maine (France). It was an alternative form of   Elizabeth  , Old French <i>Elisabet</i>, which had a shortened pet form <i>Isabet</i>. <i>Isabel</i> appears to have originated as a variant of <i>Isabet</i>, in which the suffix <i>-el</i> was substituted for <i>-et</i> through re-interpretation of <i>-et</i> as a hypocoristic diminutive. The resultant <i>-bel</i> was early associated with Old French <i>bel</i> ‘fair, beautiful’, as is evident in the French variant <i>Isabeau</i>. From France the name was taken to England, where it achieved considerable popularity in the late medieval period as an independent personal name alongside its rarer doublet <i>Elizabeth</i>. In the form <i>Isabel</i> it also appears in Spain and Portugal, while in Italy it took the form   Isabella  . The French surnames <i>Isabel</i> and   Isabelle   are particularly associated with Normandy.","History: Michel Isabel from Reux in Calvados, France, married Marie Jobidon in Château-Richer, QC, in 1673."]},{"name":"Beller","meanings":["English: occupational name for a bell founder or bell ringer, from Middle English <i>beller</i>, an agent derivative of Old English <i>belle</i> ‘bell’. Compare   Bell   2.","German: habitational name for someone from any of several places called Bell in North Rhine-Westphalia or Bellen near Bremen.","German: nickname for a quarreller, from Middle High German <i>bellen</i> ‘to bicker, quarrel’."]},{"name":"Bells","meanings":["English: variant of   Bell   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Bellman","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a bell ringer, in particular one whose duty was to make public announcements, after ringing a bell to attract attention (from Middle English <i>bel(le)man</i>, a term known to have been used in York and Scotland, and probably elsewhere, for a town crier). Compare   Bell  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>beli-man</i> ‘bellows blower’, from Middle English <i>beli</i> ‘bellows’. Compare   Bellow  .","Altered form of German   Bellmann  . This surname is also found in Sweden."]}]},{"name":"Aqua","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of English   Jaques  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jaquay","meanings":["Variant of   Jaqua  ."]},{"name":"Jaques","meanings":["English: variant of   Jacques   2 and 3.","French: variant of   Jacques   1 and, in North America, possibly also an altered form of this. Compare   Jaquith  .","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with the variant <i>Jacques</i> and its altered form <i>Jack</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":41,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":50,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":85,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":116,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],